At ORIC, our roles have helped in establishing a solid ground for facilitation and recognition of research and innovation. We aim to continue with increased diligence as we stride into the future. Our strategy for the next five years is in agreement with our mission, vision and values. We aim to prioritize research and innovation as BUITEMS main ambitions.

We engage our faculty and graduate students in the synthesis and application of globallysignificant research and innovation, delivering impact and making a difference to the community and society at a regional and national level. - We strive to establish strategic corporate and international partnerships that will make our research impactful and global. - We ensure high quality research which can improve and elevate our national and international profile as well as ranking. - We help create a research atmosphere in order to flourish young scholars of Balochistan and acquire scholarly strength.

Inauguration Technology & Innovation Support Center (TISC) at ORIC

In association with Intellectual Property Organization Pakistan (IPO) and Ministry of Science & Technology (MoST), Higher Education Commission (HEC) of Pakistan supports the formation of Technology and Innovation Support Centres to facilitate and promote, the research conducted by the University's faculty, staff and students in creation of intellectual property (IP) portfolio. Pro Vice Chancellor Dr. Faisal Khan inaugurated the TISC at ORIC on 18th December, 2020, while Deans of the respective faculties were also present during the inauguration. Pro VC Dr. Faisal Khan appreciated the efforts of ORIC team.

Purpose:

        To support access to patent database systems and science and technology

        Build technical skills for future TISC staff via training and distance learning courses

        Information and training materials

 

TISC at BUITEMS provides:

        Access to online patent database systems, intellectual property related publications and science, retrieving technology information and technology resources.

        On-demand searching (novelty, state-of-the-art and infringement)

        Technology and competitor monitoring. Also basic Information on intellectual property laws and on technology commercialisation and marketing.

 

 

COVID-19 Research at BUITEMS:

The Balochistan University of Information Technology, Engineering and Management Sciences (BUITEMS), Quetta has been at the leading edge in responding to the coronavirus (or COVID-19) pandemic. Research teams at BUITEMS are collaborating with local, regional, national and interventional organizations in the fields of Biotechnology, Microbiology, Information Technology, Electronic Engineering, Chemical Engineering, Textile Engineering, Economics and Sociology in making critically important contributions. Some of the notable works in our endeavours are:

  1. Establishment of PCR testing laboratory for COVID-19 diagnosis at Shaikh Zayed Hospital, Quetta (Established and operational)
  2. Development of indigenous ventilator BUITEMS Vent-I (Developed. Tested by DRAP for level-II use. Ready for mass-scale production)
  3. Development of Contact Tracer Application to trace COVID-19 patients for smart mitigation of the virus spread (Developed and ready for use).
  4. Development of COVID-19 infection forecast model based on artificial intelligence and machine-learning for the Government of Balochistan. (Presented to Balochistan Command & Operation Center (BCOC)
  5. Development of HAZMAT suit-A protective kit against COVID-19 (Developed. Ready for mass production).
  6. Production of low-cost disinfectant (Sodium Hypochlorite) to clean the public places-COVID 19 (Produced and handed over to city district administrator, Quetta Municipal Corporation).
  7. Production of effective and low-cost hand sanitizers by using different ingredients for COVID 19 (Produced and provided to city district administrator, Quetta Municipal Corporation).
  8. Combined Deep Learning and Molecular Docking Simulations Approach Identifying Potentially Effective FDA Approved Drugs for Repurposing against SARS-CoV-2 (Research under progress)
  9. Screening and Simulation of Highly Specific Antiviral Agents in Natural Plants Existing in the Northern Ecosystem of Balochistan: Implications to Curb COVID-19 (Research under progress)
  10. Detection of SARS-CoV-2 virus using isothermal loop-mediated isothermal amplification (LAMP) method in Balochistan (Research under progress)
  11. Assisting organizations and the government in copying with mental well-being during the pandemic (Talks organized by BUITEMS psychologists at different organizations)
  12. COVID-19 economic impact on the province and Pakistan: near-term planning and future preparedness (Research under progress)

Success of ORIC (2020-2021)

1.     ORIC Large Scale Grants

Government of Balochistan through its Research and Development program awarded Universities of Balochistan Research Fund. Under the 5th Universities Finance Commission meeting held on 13th January 2021 the distribution of funds among Universities of Balochistan were approved. The Grant-in-Aid was awarded to public sector Universities as per formula unanimously approved by all members of the Universities Finance Commission. BUITEMS secured a total of 38.27M for research studies and research development. BUITEMS-ORIC invited Research proposals from all six faculties from 1st February and collected around 56 proposals till 17th of February. After approval from ORIC Steering Committee a Technical Review Committee was set up for the scrutiny of these proposals. The committee on the basis: problem solving research, addressing local issue and SDGs, and their social impact, selected a total of 34 research proposals for further analysis.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

A selection panel was formed under the chairmanship of Dr. Faisal Ahmad Khan Pro-VC BUITEMS, with three experts Dr. Faisal F. Khan, CECOS, University Peshawar, Dr. Syed Ali Hassan, SEECS, NUST from HEIs and Dr. Hafeez Jamali, Additional Secretary (Federal Projects) from Government department as well as Mr. Dara Shikoh, Director QE&A, BUITEMS, Dr. Zahid Rauf, Dean GSO, BUITEMS and related subject experts as internal members were included. The panel procession was held on 19th and 20th March 2021. These 34 Researchers from different faculties of BUITEMS defended their proposals in the form of presentations followed by Q & A sessions. Through thorough exploration and under the policies devised by ORIC a total of 14 projects worth 38.3M were recommended.

2.     HEC Local Challenge Fund (2020-2022)

BUITEMS-ORIC shared the announced Local Challenge Fund on 17th August, 2020 with all faculty members. The Local Challenge Fund (LCF) is a funding opportunity of the Higher Education Development in Pakistan which is supported by the World Bank and implemented by the Higher Education Commission (HEC). The LCF is expected to funding research projects that address problems which are locally pertaining in the region that may include locally relevant socio-economic issues. LCF this time focuses on the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) by UN which shall be associated with the project proposals of the candidates. The local problem should address any of the 17 SDGs to support cross-disciplinary research projects. To support the local university in building research aptitude and to fund the study project of the University in answering the district level issues. A maximum of three exceptional Project Outline proposals were required by HEC and for this purpose ORIC established a technical team which scrutinized a total of 7 submitted proposals by Principal Investigators for LCF. Dr. Jan Muhammad Professor (Current VC of Turbat University) secured the award of LCF from BUITEMS.

 

 

 

3.     National Grassroots ICT Research Initiative (NGIRI) - FYP by Ignite (2020-2021)

Ignite National Technology Fund by the Government of Pakistan and administered by the Ministry of Information Technology and Telecommunication announced its National Grassroots ICT Research Initiative (NGIRI)- a program that aims to assist final year undergraduate students of ICT related disciplines studying in the institutions by providing them financial assistance for developing prototypes / working models of their Final Year Projects (FYP) in order to increase creativity, innovation and hands on engineering and development skills. Undergraduate students from BUITEMS belonging from Faculty of Information and Communication Technology and Faculty of Engineering and Architecture applied. A total of 71 projects were submitted under NGIRI-FYP around of which 61 projects were approved by Ignite Islamabad Headquarters among which 22 FYP were selected for funding award. As per instructions and guidelines set by Ignite Deputy Director ORIC Syed Usman delivered an informative session on NGIRI program and discussed the selection criteria, along with further procedures, to the supervisors and students. FYP are selected for funding with following financial breakup: Equipment: Maximum up to Rs.70,000/- and Miscellaneous: Maximum up to Rs. 10,000/-. Its an achievement for BUITEMS that almost 80 students will be benefited.

 


Research Projects

For researchers at BUITEMS, success is defined through expansion of fundamental knowledge and the transition of lab results to the real world. Therefore, our research is not only restricted to theory and postulates, we are aiming towards ideas and solutions that make a direct impact on the society. Research at BUITEMS currently focuses on solutions in the sectors of technology, engineering, architecture, social sciences and economics, applied natural sciences, agriculture and biomedical science. In the field of technology and engineering, the works include development of robotics and artificial intelligence for disaster management applications, GIS-based solutions for a variety of applications, cutting edge work on virtual learning technology for the unconnected areas of the province; BUITEMS researchers are also working on establishing a state-of-the-art digital and bio forensic centre that will help improve citizen safety. In the field of engineering, BUITEMS researchers are busy studying regional problems in architecture, construction and irrigation and are coming up with the most feasible solutions to the problems. In the fields of social sciences and economics, the works include the study of local economy and devising new ways of feasible and prolific business in the local setting, socio-economic impact of COVID-19 and resilient economics, works on applied linguistics in indigenous languages. In the fields of agriculture and biomedical sciences the works focus on the contemporary regional problems including the study of environmentally feasible commercial agriculture, the study of deforestation of juniper, and the study and cure of medical disorders pertinent to the region. Brief details of research projects approved and conducted during 2020-201 by the faculty are provided below. The projects are funded by international and national funding agencies and from BUITEMS own resources.

Textile Engineering- FoE&A

Development of IR camouflage shelters utilizing Balochi Wool based composites.
 


In this work we propose to use wool fibers which are intrinsically IR resistant having good strength and low environmental factor. The wool fibers when mixed with matrix like resins and reinforcing agent can be converted into rigid sheet like structures which can be utilized to make shelter directly or as insulation layers on already existed structure. This methodology can provide a low cost and light weight IR shielding material which can be directly beneficial for defense purposes where IR shielding is required to camouflage to hide personals or valuable commodities. Furthermore, the utilization of local raw material can provide opportunities to local industries and breeder of Pakistan in general and Balochistan in particular.

Recycling of Domestic Waste Water using low-cost visible light Photodegradation technique to Overcome Water scarcity and Water Quality Improvement for Quetta City

 
 

 


The Quetta Valley is encountering the adverse impacts of climate change and continuous groundwater depletion. The groundwater resources of Quetta Valley are under stress because these are the sole source of Water Supply and all other usage for provincial capital. This research work is focused on presenting a sustainable solution for treating the domestic effluent of Quetta city using solar light based photocatalysis. Research will focus on removal of organic matter and other impurities from wastewater and sustainable growth mechanism is devised where this treated water will be utilized to overcome groundwater depletion. Visible light Photodegradation is cost effective technique to remove organic matter and microbes from wastewater using abundantly available solar light. Zinc Tin Oxide and Zinc Oxide composite, a state of the art nanocomposite is being be used as photocatalyst with having high electron mobility to reduce the contaminants. There is nonfunctional wastewater treatment system in city. This study is integrated with existing water treatment plant at Sabzal Road Quetta and in collaboration with B-WASA Quetta research and design data of this work will pave the way for sustainable rehabilitation of plant and ground water depletion.

Research Labs

1. Control, Automotive & Robotics Lab CARL

 

Established under the National Centre for Robotics & Automation (NCRA)

Control, Automotive & Robotics Lab (CARL) research team at BUITEMS is a research cluster that has been working on the development of robot-assisted systems to solve pressing problems of Pakistan, and particularly Balochistan, using Robotics and Artificial Intelligence. The lab is part of a consortium of 11 Labs in 13 Universities under the name National Centre of Robotics & Automation (NCRA). The lab consists of qualified Ph.D.s, industry researchers, and experts to achieve solutions to local problems. CARL is currently working on a project worth 80 million PKR funded by the NCRA to research and develop a search and rescue snake robot and social mobile autonomous robot in the form of an autonomous waiter robot.

NCRA is a PSDP project worth 1.295 B under the umbrella of HEC. The National Centre of Robotics and Automation is a consortium of Universities of Pakistan with its Centre headquarter at NUST College of EME, Rawalpindi. The Centre proposes to become the leading hub of think, design, innovate, and commercialize to transfer knowledge to the local economy in the area of Robotics and Automation, to facilitate the researchers in the field of Robotics and Automation, help them establish and grow Automation industry towards Industry 4.0 and seek solutions to the indigenous problems through Robotics and Automation.

The Team

Domains

Search and Rescue Robot: Hyper-redundant snake-robot that uses state-of-the-art reinforcement learning algorithms to maneuver in complex environments such as collapsed buildings and coal mines to identify human survivors. These robots should be preferred because they can move in very narrow places, on different terrains on the ground and in the water where the wheeled and legged robots fail. Our goal is to make this robot close to a natural snake as much as possible to exploit its flexible movements. Our long-term goal is to turn our snake robot project from a prototype into an actual machine that can be deployed in earthquake-affected places and save lives by bringing state-of-the-art rescue equipment for disaster relief teams in Pakistan.

Social Mobile Autonomous Robot SMART: Social robots can interact with humans to provide information and guidance. They have multiple applications including being stationed at Airports, Universities, and public gatherings, we are focusing on its food serving application. Future versions will include local language understanding. The goal of SMART is to overcome human-robot social barriers. Towards this end, we are in the process of developing a second robotic prototype that bears a personality and which can behave according to social conventions. The idea is that communication and interaction with robots should be easy and enjoyable. The robot will be able to navigate autonomously in our labs, by knowing its exact location. The robot will be like a customizable chatbot from which people can ask their concerned queries and the robot would be able to answer every general query using Artificial intelligence.

Incubates

        Microsoft Imagine Cup Regional Winner (South Region) Muhammad Rafi & Kabisha Anwar

This project was focuses on a semi-autonomous robot, WhegRoach, capable of taking smart decisions and giving internal view to the rescues team, so that they can go safely and perform their respective tasks. The design of the robot enables it to overcome different obstacles and move stably on rough terrains. It can be used for space exploration, crops field, SAR tasks and mining areas to perform perilous tasks.

Abstract:

By manipulation with time, temperature, hardener, and liquid crystal (LC) applied magnetics stirrer during addition polymerization chemical reaction leading to the formation of neat epoxy resin based smart films panel. Patent 2:

The PCR based cost-effective 100bp DNA LADDER.

Applicants:

1. Dr. Anwar Khan, PhD, Assistant Professor

2. Dr. Nusrat Jahan PhD, Associate Professor, BUITEMS

 

3. Dr. Naseebullah Kakar, PhD, Associate Professor, BUITEMS

 

Abstract:

Standard units for the measurement of quantitative descriptions of natural phenomena are the foundation of scientific examination. In genomics, the DNA ladder is used as a standard unit that express the quantitative standard unit for the measurement of unknown DNA Fragments, plasmids, and PCR products in gel electrophoresis. The 100 base pair DNA ladder is essential and cost-effective in molecular biological research and is available commercially which is too expensive and not easily accessible to a common researcher for his/her research they have to place an order, Wait from several weeks to months for dispatch, and pay the colossal sum of money as well. Therefore, the purpose of this study was to report a simple and practical method to prepare a 100 bp. DNA ladder by simple PCR method using pCAMBIA 1301 plasmid as a template that would be an effective cost reduction strategy for laboratories. About 10 pairs of primers from 100 bp up to 1000bp were designed from the backbone of the vector with an interval of 100 bp. Each fragment was amplified using thermocycler and resolved on gel electrophoresis. Results of this study showed that PCR method was able to amplify 10 amplify 10 different DNA fragments ranging from 100 to 1000 bp with high qualification and size accuracy. We purified PCR products and the fragments were sequenced, the size and stability of the fragments were right and showed high quality and quantity for each band of the ladder.

 

Specification:

In every field of science, scientific examination depends on standard units for the measurement of quantitative descriptions of natural phenomena. Biotechnology research involves very excessive chemicals, enzymes and also various molecular biology kits and other commercial products. This is a work that visualizes establishing primary molecular biology protocols in the lab to produce economical kits and products which will bring down the operational expenses. The 100 bp DNA ladders have high economic importance as these ladders are used regularly in research laboratories to carry out different experimental works. DNA ladder also called a molecular weight marker is basically a mixture of different know double-stranded DNA fragments. DNA ladder is an important tool used to determine the fragment size of the unknown PCR products in the gel electrophoresis. Consequently, DNA Ladder has been prepared with in low cost. The fragments of DNA ladder are mixed and encoded within a single molecule for laboratory usage and can be produced by different laboratories. For the development of the prototype plant expression vector, pCAMBIA 1301 was used as a templet. The fragments were purified subsequently, and quantified using nano-drop and sequenced.

Claims:   

The invention is claimed to be cost effective product 100bp ladder compared to the existing commercial product that is used in variety of molecular biology and biotechnology experiments.

Patent 4:

Synthesis of Ionic Liquids and Heterogeneous Catalysts for biodiesel Production from Jatropha Oil and their detail Comparative Study.

Applicants

1. Dr. Zahoor Ullah, Department of Chemistry, Faculty of Arts & Basic Sciences, Balochistan University of Information Technology, Engineering and Management Sciences (BUITEMS). Quetta 87300 Pakistan. (Pakistani).

 

2. Mujtaba Ellahi, Department of Chemistry, Faculty of Arts & Basic Sciences, Balochistan University of Information Technology, Engineering and Management Sciences (BUITEMS).

Abstract

Energy demand is special concern of the today world. Due to diminishing of world fossils fuel, researchers seek suitable renewable fuels. Biodiesel is one of the good alternatives as renewable fuel. The biodiesel production cost is very high compared to petrodiesel due cost of feedstock, so less expensive feedstock is of special concern, which include non-edible oils, waste cooking oil, animal fats that are derived from renewable feedstock such as vegetable oils and animals fats. Biodiesel can be produced by transesterification of high FFAs feedstock, vegetable oil or animals fats triacylglycerol in the presence of alcohol and suitable catalysts. The product obtained is fatty acid methylester so called biodiesel and byproduct glycerin.

Specification:

In this research work, Some ionic liquids and heterogeneous catalysts were prepared and characterized with different analytical techniques for structure confirmation. All the synthesized catalysts (ILs + Heterogeneous catalysts) were screened initially for biodiesel production from Jatroph curcas oil (high FFAs oil) and keep all the parameters in same condition during process. The best catalyst was chosen from both catalyst types and further optimized for detail study to get the high yield of biodiesel. Both the catalysts yield was reasonable but comparatively the IL yield was better and more than 90% with high recyclability was. Activity of catalysts was optimized with reference to different parameters which include variable catalyst loading, methanol to oil molar ratio, reaction time and reaction temperature. The final biodiesel product was analysed with gas chromatography (GC), nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) and thermal gravimetric (TGA) techniques. The physicochemical properties were also investigated and were according to the standards when compared with international established standards.

Claims:

Biodiesel production from Jatroph curcas oil (high FFAs oil).

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Patent 5:

Developing a lightest bullet proof vest by developing a comprehensive conceptual model and vice versa.

Applicants

1. Dr. Zameer ul Hassan, PhD, Associate Professor, Chairperson Textile Engineering/ Fashion & Textile Design (BUITEMS).

Abstract

Recently smart electronic wearables have gained reputation as assistive devices in sports, healthcare, human machine interface (HMI), sign language and telemedicine. Despite of their increasing popularity, the electronic sensing elements in these wearables are rigid, uncomfortable and costly. Instead of these rigid sensors E-textile based sensors provide increased comfort, flexibility and applicability. Gesture recognition gloves are getting increasingly popular as human-machine interface devices. This glove is flexible, more comfortable and cost-effective as compared to the conventional human machine interface gloves. In this work a conductive yarn with piezoresistive properties is integrated in a glove, the yarn is integrated in such a way that it is stretched and compressed with the movement of finger joints. Resistance of this yarn changes as it is stretched or compressed, this change is notable and can be used to monitor hand gestures. A portable system was designed to monitor analog data for each gesture. The raw data was processed in MATLAB computation software.

 

 

Specification:

Data glove was used by NASA to interact with the simulated airflow around an aircraft at NASA laboratories. Machines have been close companions to human beings for decades. The rapid increase in number of machines means more interactions with us. The recent developments in human machine interface technology are focused upon developing more efficient ways of communication between humans and machines. As we use hand gestures extensively in our everyday communication with human beings, these gestures can also be used to communicate with the machines. In order to recognize these gestures and use those to control machines two main approaches are used; the first approach is to use visual based recognition systems that extract gesture data from graphic images; the second approach is to use haptic data recognition glove based systems. The latter glove based systems are better than the visual based systems because these are cheap, portable and require less processing power.

 

Claims:

A 3d printed robotic hand was controlled with the glove to demonstrate its application in teleoperations. The fabricated glove can effectively sense our gestures and can be used for various applications specifically in sign language and HMI.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Patent 6:

Smart glove for deaf & dumb to recognize sign language and Human Machine Interface Using Wirelessly Communicated Piezoresistive Textile Based Sensors.

Applicants:

1. Dr. Zameer ul Hassan, PhD, Associate Professor, Chairperson Textile Engineering/ Fashion & Textile Design (BUITEMS).

Abstract

It is suggested to develop an antiballistic model to develop Ultra-light weight bullet proof jacket equipped with textile-based shielding for the high protection performance. It would be highly resistant to bullet penetration and more effective than the old bullet proof jacket. It will have the properties such as light weight than the currently used vests, which would be very easy to carry. Secondly it would be more comfortable. It would have the property of storing the bullet for the evidence rather than to reflect it back. Our main goal would be focused to reduce the weight of vest and increase the protection performance. This would not only be beneficial for army, law enforcement agencies and security guards but also for a common man who has suffered a lot of loss in our imposed war against terrorism.

Specification:

In the 1500s, solid metal armor designed to withstand firearms. It was made up of Milan, possibly of Damascus steel. In the English Civil War (1642 - 1651) Oliver Cromwell's cavalry were equipped with double-layered metal cuirasses (vests) that were designed to be bullet proof. When a 16th century European blacksmith finished making armor that was impervious to firearms, he fired a shot at the breastplate, denting it. As the story goes, this dent was proof to his customer that the armor would stand up to a bullet, so it became known as "the bullet proof." Since then, the history of bulletproof vests has been anything but a straight shot. In the late 1800s, both Japan and Korea developed some of the first modern bulletproof vests when they discovered that 30 layers of silk fabric could stop the black powder bullets of the day. This "soft armor" laid the foundation for numerous inventors who tried to improve upon the idea as firearms became more powerful.

Claims:

The normal bulletproof jacket used in Pakistan is very heavy approximately its weight is 15 to 18 kg and having low protection features. It is very difficult to carry the weighted bullet proof jacket in wars. Secondly it cannot be used by Females and childrens due to high weight. We are producing a Bulletproof jacket with many features such as Light weight, High protection and can be used by Females and childrens too.

Pakistan is the 33rd-largest country by area, spanning 881,913 square kilometers in which Balochistan has 347,190 square kilometers of 43% of Pakistan and has a 1046-kilometre coastline along the Arabian Sea in which 770 km from Balochistan of 70% of total coastal line of the country.
